Charlotte was not alone. Border Patrol units were redeployed from Chicago to the Raleigh\'96Durham area, again targeting immigrant neighborhoods and again prompting fear and disruption. A federal judge in Chicago, reviewing an earlier operation called \'93Midway Blitz,\'94 learned that more than 97% of those detained there had no criminal convictions, despite official claims that the raids focused on \'93violent criminal illegal aliens.\'94 The judge reprimanded a Border Patrol official for attacks on peaceful protesters and reminded the agency that it could not treat constitutional limits as optional. These facts undercut the administration\'92s public narrative and showed how far enforcement had drifted from any narrow public\uc0\u8209 safety rationale. The law on paper still required warrants and probable cause. The law in practice, for many immigrants and even some citizens, now meant masked agents in unmarked cars and the risk of being swept up for being in the wrong place at the wrong time.\
