The use of uniformed power to manage domestic politics extended beyond immigration. National Guard troops were deployed into cities such as Portland, Chicago, and Washington, D.C., without the consent of local leaders. These deployments blurred the line between military service and political theater. They were justified as responses to unrest and border pressures, but they also served as visible symbols of federal dominance over urban centers that tended to oppose the president. At the same time, the Pentagon under Defense Secretary Pete Hegseth removed senior officers, including the navy chief of staff and the chair of the Joint Chiefs, CQ Brown Jr., as part of a stated plan to cut four\uc0\u8209 star billets. A group of former service secretaries and retired four\u8209 star officers issued a public report warning that these moves, combined with domestic deployments, were politicizing the armed forces. They urged Congress to require clear justifications and after\u8209 action reviews for major domestic uses of troops and for high\u8209 level firings. Their warning underscored how the week\'92s security decisions were not isolated but part of a broader effort to align the instruments of force with the preferences of one leader.\
