If force on the streets showed one face of power, the treatment of transgender people showed another: the quiet but sweeping use of executive orders and guidance to redraw the boundaries of legal personhood. Executive Order 14168, signed at the start of the term but felt in full during this week, rolled back federal recognition of transgender identities. The \'93X\'94 gender marker disappeared from passports. Requests to update gender markers were denied, and some passports were revoked. Federal websites removed LGBTQ health pages and suicide\uc0\u8209 risk data. Trans\u8209 related terminology vanished from surveys and guidance. Hospitals, schools, and researchers lost access to information they had used to understand and support a vulnerable population. This was not a single policy dispute. It was an attempt to erase a category of people from the state\'92s own records, making their needs harder to see and their claims harder to prove.\
